<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-377-632  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 377 632.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  May 1989 p25(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>On Ford's quality drive. (Ford Motor in Britain-automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mancey, Jo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Ford Motor Company Ltd has restructured its entire UK operation ina 92-million pounds sterling automation program.andP;  The companysought to ensure high quality and low cost in its new Fiesta modelby investing in new manufacturing equipment.andP;  New machines andbetter materials have improved body construction and assembly.andO;CAD-CAM systems supplied by Prime Computer reduce the number ofspot welds required to build the car body.andP;  Increasing the amountof automated welding and reducing manual welding allows a moreconsistent quality standard, while a statistical process-controlpackage running on a microcomputer improves the quality of thewelds themselves.andP;  Ford installed more than 200 new Kuka and Asearobots to raise the amount of automated welding to the requiredlevel.andP;  The new automation has raised both quality levels andproductivity by speeding up the manufacturing process.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Ford Motor Company Ltd. (automation).andO;Topic:     Factory ManagementAutomationCost ReductionQuality ControlCAD-CAMIndustrial RobotsCase Study.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>